at%20room%20temperature%2C%20nothing%20added)%2C%20on%20the%20rocks%20(with%20ice)%2C%20and%20with%20a%20bit%20of%20water.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20recommend%20first%20trying%20a%20bourbon%20neat.%20From%20there%2C%20you%20can%20decide%20how%20you%20want%20it.%20A%20little%20water%2C%20just%20a%20few%20drops%2C%20will%20unlock%20new%20flavors%2C%20especially%20in%20higher-proof%20bourbons.%20A%20large%20ice%20cube%20will%20cool%20the%20bourbon%20and%20melt%20slowly%20to%20avoid%20diluting%20it%20too%20much.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EGenerally%2C%20though%2C%20bourbon%20drinkers%20frown%20upon%20shooting%20bourbon%20or%20mixing%20it%20with%20soda.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fguides%2Fkitchen%2Fhow-to-drink-bourbon%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ECheck%20out%20our%20full%20article%20on%20how%20to%20drink%20bourbon%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Ch3%3EHow%20is%20bourbon%20made%3F%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3EBourbon%20is%20made%20with%20grains%2C%20primarily%20corn.%20The%20milled%20grains%20are%20cooked%20to%20make%20a%20porridge-like%20mash.%20The%20mash%20is%20fermented%20for%20a%20few%20days%20and%20then%20distilled.%20The%20distillate%20is%20then%20put%20into%20charred%20oak%20barrels%20and%20aged.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBourbon%20must%20be%20at%20least%2051%25%20corn.%20Almost%20all%20bourbons%20contain%20malted%20barley%2C%20and%20most%20have%20rye%20or%20wheat%20as%20a%20secondary%20grain.%20Once%20the%20ground%20grains%20are%20mixed%20with%20water%20and%20cooked%2C%20the%20sour%20mash%20is%20cooled%20before%20entering%20a%20fermenter%20where%20yeast%20is%20added.%20The%20yeast%20feeds%20on%20the%20sugars%20in%20the%20mash%2C%20turning%20them%20into%20alcohol.%20The%20distilleries%20I%20visited%20ferment%20the%20mash%20for%20three%20or%20four%20days.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20fermented%20mash%20is%20essentially%20beer.%20The%20%26quot%3Bbeer%26quot%3B%20goes%20to%20the%20still%20from%20the%20fermenters%2C%20where%20it%20is%20heated%20to%20extract%20the%20alcohol.%20The%20distilled%20spirit%20is%20known%20as%20%26quot%3Bwhite%20dog.%26quot%3B%20The%20white%20dog%20goes%20into%20new%20charred%20oak%20barrels%20and%20is%20aged%20for%20between%20a%20few%20months%20and%20several%20years.%20%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20the%20aged%20bourbon%20is%20ready%2C%20it's%20filtered%20and%20usually%20%26quot%3Bproofed%20down%26quot%3B%20by%20adding%20purified%20water%20to%20lower%20the%20alcohol%20percentage.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Ch3%3EWhat%20is%20a%20bourbon%20mash%20bill%3F%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3EBourbon%20is%20made%20with%20different%20grains.%20The%20grain%20percentages%20used%20to%20create%20a%20bourbon%20make%20up%20the%20mash%20bill.%20All%20bourbons%20have%20a%20mash%20bill%20with%20at%20least%2051%25%20corn.%20There's%20also%20usually%20malted%20barley%20and%20either%20rye%20or%20wheat.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMost%20bourbons%20use%20rye%20as%20a%20secondary%20grain.%20According%20to%20Minnick%2C%20rye%20typically%20imparts%20different%20spices%20to%20the%20nose%20and%20palate%20of%20a%20bourbon.%20For%20instance%2C%20high%20rye%20bourbons%20tend%20to%20have%20cinnamon%20notes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMinnick%20has%20found%20that%20high%20barley%20bourbons%20offer%20more%20spicy%20nutmeg%20notes.%20While%20wheated%20bourbons%20tend%20to%20impart%20caramel%2C%20though%20charred%20oak%20barrels%20give%20all%20bourbons%20a%20degree%20of%20caramel%20flavoring.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20you%20are%20looking%20for%20new%20bourbons%2C%20the%20mash%20bill%20is%20an%20excellent%20place%20to%20start.%20Look%20for%20bourbons%20that%20have%20a%20similar%20mash%20bill%20to%20those%20you%20like.%20%3C%2Fp%3E%3Chr%3E%3Ch3%3EWhat%20are%20the%20best%20bourbon%20cocktails%3F%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3EThree%20cocktails%20that%20are%20traditionally%20made%20with%20bourbon%20are%20the%20Old%20Fashioned%2C%20Manhattan%2C%20and%20Mint%20Julep.%20For%20details%20on%20making%20these%20and%20other%20bourbon%20cocktails%2C%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C